Key points for Axel presentation

I History
II Recommendations
a. Demonstrate an understanding of the history and culture of the client organization and its relevance to the case.

\Intro
When I first heard we were doing a case study on Axel Springer, I was pumped. "Welcome to the Jungle," "Sweet Child 'O Mine," I'm a huge Guns 'N Roses fan. But it turns out Axel Springer SE is not the lead singer of Guns 'N Roses. That's Axel Rose. Axel Springer is a German publishing company. So even though Axel Springer SE is not among the top 6 rock and roll bands of all time, it is among the top six largest digital publishers worldwide after it's recent acquisition of BusinessInsider.com.

\Michael Dopfner
Michael Dopfner, Axel Springer CEO, has a presence all his own. He is tall enough for professional basketball at 6 feet 5 inches in height. Not only is Dopfner's presence powerful by size alone, he has the smarts to go with it. Dopfner has a PhD in Musicology from the University of Frankfurt and was a music critic before becoming the youngest CEO of Axel Springer SE in 2002, at age 39. When asked about his unusual path to CEO recently, he told an interviewer it was almost unheard of in Germany, saying, "That's actually not allowed."

\Bild.de
Axel Springer SE's largest publication is a tabloid (Bild), but the CEO makes headlines worldwide as a principled, traditional, serious, future-oriented thought leader. At the time of the Stanford Business school case study, Dopfner's focus was to move Axel Springer SE from print revenue to half of all revenue from digital publishing. That was in 2014, but already Dopfner has taken Axel Springer SE to 75 percent revenue from digital publishing, as indicated on its corporate website as of this week.

\Google Results: "Michael Dopfner"
If you Google Michael Dopfner right now on your phone, the top result is likely an announcement that Axel Springer SE acquired BusinessInsider.com in part of its strategy to become the world's top digital publsher. Other results may include Dopfner's interview of Facebook CEO, Mark Zuckerberg, about the future of digital media. You may see that Jeff Bezos, CEO of Amazon, has a personal equity company that owns stock in Axel Springer SE. Finally, you may also see links to Plug And Play, Axel Springer SE's accelerator for entrepreneurs in Silicon Valley and Berlin. Out of all the excitement, it is easy to look to the future of digital publishing, because Dopfner's vision is so clear. But to really understand Dopfner's vision for Axel Springer SE, the story starts in the past.

\History
It was 1946 (check) and a man named Axel Springer began a publishing company in Germany. Following World War II, it goes without saying these were times of social and political change in Germany. The press was especially important in giving a voice and sharing messages with the people of Germany, who were collectively finding a new normal for their society after their nation was hijacked by Hitler's Third Reich. Through these times, Axel Springer was known for truth in journalism. Impartial, honest, factual, high-integrity journalism was the core of Axel Springer's works. Fast forwarding a bit, the company relocated its headquarters to an office building overlooking the Berlin wall. They were, to borrow a sports analogy, at the 50-yard line and right in front of the action. They could see both sides of the wall from the office windows.

\Political Influence Continues
In some ways, this relocation was a powerful battle cry for what kind of company Axel Springer aimed to be. True to those roots today, Dopfner fights that good fight to preserve journalism as an important profession benefitting society. Journalism itself is threatened by low quality coverage without fact checks, in Dopfner's logic. Journalism, in the traditional sense, transcends print vs. digital media and will prevail. People need journalism to promote fairness and truth in human civilization. Axel Springer SE is uniquely qualified to act as a worldwide defender of journalism, having experienced first-hand what can happen when one party had too much control of the media in World War II Germany.

\Open Letter to Google
It is from this historical and social context that Dopfner wrote his open letter to Google about controlling what news people saw. Dopfner, and Axel Springer SE, are business persons who strongly believe journalism should be a paid, specialized profession.

\Facebook Denied
Following the influence of social media on the recent American presidential election, Facebook asked European publishers to fact check social media posts to help an algorithm block misinformation. Perhaps unsurpringly, Dopfner took a strong and public stance to say no. He said it was not the business of serious journalists and publishers to get involved with the problems of social media. All European media companies side with Dopfner except one small publisher in France with 20 employees, which is a drop in the bucket of all European Union publishers.

b. Identify and evaluate critical decisions made in the evolution of the case.

\Mid-presentation Recap
Since it's afternoon now, you have probably already heard many times how Bild was a crucial revenue stream for Axel Springer as it transitioned into a digital revenue model. One thing other consultants may not have reflected is the magnitude of this irony. The largest publication owned by Axel Springer SE is a tabloid called Bild. It's been the big print media revenue maker for decades at Axel Springer. It was also a huge success as a website, the particulars of which we will address momentarily. Yet the fact that such a large portion of the revenue is from a tabloid does not seem to undermine Axel Springer SE's reputation as a high-integrity, international defender of journalistic innovation and civil truth. Hey, we all like diversity, right? It makes the world a better place and gives strength by joining us together in differing worldviews, opinions, values, etc. Here's a great example with Axel Spr. and Bild.

I think that speaks to how strong the brand is. To celebrate Axel Springer's success with the tabloid, some of the later slides in this presentation are written in Tabloid format. I think you will see how hard it is to pull off a tabloid component in the context of a serious business consulting proposal. Hard to do, but that's exactly what their CEO has been doing with Axel Springer SE successfully for 15 years.

